THE YGUANA.

The yguana, an animal of the lizard kind, closely resembles the dragon which St. George is represented overthrowing. It is some* times more than an ell long. Its belly is large, its skin clothed with green, white, and yellow scales, elegantly varied with red. From the head to the extremity of the tail, the spine of the back is surmounted by a denticulated fin. Its thick and very long tail is marked with kinds of black rings, intermixed with red ones, and ends in a very slender point. It is furnished with large* black eyes, a nose spreading as wide as the lips, short teeth, a cloven tongue‚ which, when irri- tated, it moves very quickly, four feet, and lower down five nails, wide like the sole of th'e foot, and covered with a thin web, which assists it in swimming· 3 sor it sometimes swims in the water, ’ sometimes climbs trees, and sometimes lurks for· a long time in corners of houses, being very pa- tient of hunger. It never does harm to any one.
